      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "While Western societies exemplify modern structures, the concept broadly applies to highly industrialized, globally interconnected societies beyond just the West. The development is often viewed not as a single natural ascent, but as a complex, punctuated process involving historical shifts like the Enlightenment, industrial revolutions, and globalization. Many scholars debate whether this evolution is truly linear or if different societies have developed varied pathways to modernity. Therefore, viewing it as a potential progression rather than a strict, inevitable march is often a more nuanced approach.",
      "source": "target",
